fields.name: Álftanes Deep Sea Divers
fields.description: In 2016, the Divers made one unLucky start-sit decision that ended up making the difference between the Champion and the 3rd place finish. They did make the playoffs though and are the only team to ever make the playoff with more losses than wins. In 2017, the team won only one game against his own division, which resulted in the bottom of the group. General Manager Andri was active in the trading scene and come draft he had 6 picks in the first 2 rounds. The roster is young and probably isn't ready just yet, but given poor division, they might just squeeze in the playoffs.
fields.quarterbacks: The Divers traded for Drew Brees before the 2017 season started, but traded him away once the playoffs were out of reach. The move was necessary as their star Quarterback, Andrew Luck wasn't ready for week 1. It turned out, he wasn't even ready for week 17, but is supposidly back to full strength, which the team really needs, considering the backups. Joe Flacco is backup up Luck, but who knows for how long as he has a very promising rookie breathing down his neck. Flacco ended the year strong, but was hardly usable for the regular season. The other backup might also be out of job soon, Josh McCown might not even start week 1. B-
fields.running_backs: The Running Backs for the Divers don't have a lot of experience, the most experienced one being Jordan Howard who is entering his 3rd season. He has surpassed 1000 yards both years, a should do it again this year. But for him to reach the top, he has to get more involved in the passing game. Derrick Henry is also entering his 3rd season, but has spent the first 2 watching DeMarco Murray lead the charts. Now that he is retired, he finally gets the lead job. Titans getting Dion Lewis caps his upside a bit though. In the first 9 picks of this years rookie, GM Andri picked 3 Running Backs, Ronald Jones, Nick Chubb and Royce Freeman. Freeman is most likely to contribute in the first year, given the lack of competition in Denver. RoJo should also make an impact for the Buccaneers after they released Doug Martin. Although Chubb is probably the best of the bunch, he has some competition ahead of him in Cleveland. B+
fields.receivers: The $13 spent on, the then rookie, Michael Thomas in the startup draft looks to be one of the best values of the draft. He has recorded over 1000 yards in his first 2 seasons and is projected for even more yards in 2018. At this point last year, Mike Evans was in consideration for the 1st overall pick in dynasty startups. After having the worst year of his carreer in 20017 (though still managin 1000 yards) he has dropped to bit in the ranks, but is still considered a top 10 asset. The Divers are missing a strong WR3 option, but rookie Courtland Sutton comes closest. Although playing behind 2 veterans in Denver, Sutton was drafted to be the new king in town. DeVante Parker was an early draft pick by the Dolphins in 2015, but in his 3 year carreer, he has yet to show that he is worth that draft spot. If he doesn't shine this year, now that Jarvis Landry has moved to Cleveland, he probably never will. Rookie Michael Gallup is another player who can will some space left by a veteren, as Dez Bryant left town. Tre'Quan Smith was drafted in back of the 3rd round and is an interesting prospect. He still has to beat old timer Ted Ginn and newly signed Cameron Meredith for the job as a receiver with Michael Thomas. Newly acquired Trey Burton leads a questionable Tight End group. Although he only has 6 Touchdowns in his 3 year career, Chicago has high hopes for the newly signed Bear. Jack Doyle has had 2 strong years now and shuold get Andrew Luck back throwing him the ball, which is always a plus. Tyler Eifert, a once 1st round draft pick hasn't lived up to expectations. Although, when he plays, he scores a Touchdown at least every other game. WR: A-, TE: B-
fields.all_eyes_on: Jarvis Landry held the record for most receptions in his first two NFL seasons with 194. Michael Thomas broke that record in 2016-2017 with 196 catches. It certainly helps having a Hall-of-Fame QB throwing the ball, and while Drew Brees turned 39 earlier this year, he did not show a decline in ability. It was rather a shift in the offense to a wildly successful run game with Ingram & Kamara leading the way, that led to a drop in passing TD numbers. Still, Thomas’ receptions and receiving yards went up. Michael Thomas may not deliver monster weeks, but seems like a lock to finish as a Top 10 WR again.
fields.x_factor: After a huge breakout season in 2016 with over 1300 receiving yards and 12 TDs, some fantasy owners put Evans in the Bust category for 2017. He was drafted in the 1st Round of fantasy drafts, and finished as the WR17. Evans never delivered any big week-winning performances, which he did so often in 2016. He’s still a young, supreme talent that should bounce back in 2018. Drafting him mid-late 2nd Round is much more appealing than his 1st Round price tag from last year’s drafts.
fields.key_to_championship: You can win a championship without a top-tier Quarterback, but it's a lot harder when you have Joe Flacco in the position. The Divers need a stable showing from Luck to do anything. To be pushed over the top, some of these newly drafted rookies must hit, big time.
fields.scouting_report: "The Divers roster looked amazing just 1 year ago and got a full house in the league poll to make the playoffs. Things didn't go as planned and now the team doesn't look as good. But the team is very young and could compete in a year or 2. For now, they should be a middle of the pack team."

fields.name: Brussels Bruisers
fields.description: In the first 2 pre-season polls, most people predicted the Bruisers to playoffs but the team got 2 and 4 wins respectively. Last season, the other general managers lost faith and few voted for the team. The team has been unlucky with injuries in the past, but has moved on by trading many players away. But in that process they are left with a team without superstars. It's going to be a while until they reach their first playoffs.
fields.quarterbacks: The Bruisers used their first pick (1.05) on a quarterback, Kyler Murray, the 1st overall pick by the Cardinals. Some might think it was a bit early, but given the strength of this years draft and the type of player Murray is, it might just work out. A running quarterbacks gives your team a great baseline. To back him up the team has Jameis Winston, who might even start a few games in the beginning while Murray gets up to speed with the NFL. Lastly, Josh Rosen (last years 1st round pick by the Cardinals) might get some redemption in Miami.
fields.running_backs: Kerryon Johnson is the player the Bruisers' GM must build around. He showed what he is capable of last year in Detroit and now he has the running back job for himself. Tarik Cohen will probably never be more than a 3rd down back or a change-of-pace back and would be serviceable on a fantasy team as a flex/bye week option, but when he's your 2nd best running back, you've got some holes to fill. Ronald Jones was a polarising player before last season, people either loved him or hated him. He didn't get many opportunities, but with a new coach, this highly drafted player might get a chance. With the exception of Kalen Ballage, the rest of the running backs probably won't get any playing time this year.
fields.receivers: The closest resemblance to a superstar on the Bruisers' roster has to be Keenan Allen. But like all the best players on the roster, he has had some troubles with injuries. The highly drafted Corey Davis hasn't panned out the way people hoped and this season will be a make-or-break for him to show something. Dede Westbrook is part of receiving corps in Jacksonville that people are having a hard time figuring out who the lead player will be. It could well be Westbrook. Tre'Quan Smith is an interesting prospect, a player fighting for the WR2 spot on the Saints. As long as Drew Brees is throwing the ball, that spot is a good spot to be in. All though there aren't many good fantasy tight ends in the league, Bruisers's ones aren't exactly spectacular. The GM spent his early 2nd round pick on Hakeem Butler, a player analysts were really high on before the draft,  but fell a lot lower on draft day. It will be fun to see if he can prove the doubters wrong. Mark Andrews will be the starting tight end, but he's on a team that 1) has a lot of tight ends, 2) spent 2 high draft picks on receivers and 3) throw the ball fewer times than the average team in the league. To back him up is Cameron Brate, not only a backup for the fantasy team, also a backup for the Buccaneers.
fields.all_eyes_on: Despite having an extremely limited role to start the season, Johnson finished as the RB18 in points per game during his rookie season. The Lions did sign C.J. Anderson, but Johnson has already shown he's able to produce with a veteran on the roster, and he's openly admitted that he doesn't want to be a 20-plus touch running back. He's not going to offer top-five upside, but Johnson should be an RB2 more often than not.
fields.x_factor: Kyler only had one full season as a starter in college. Taking over for Baker Mayfield, Kyler was able to put up nearly identical numbers across the board to 2018’s No. 1 NFL pick...and he did it throwing 20 fewer passes...while adding over 1,000 rushing yards. The Cards saw enough to make him their No. 1 pick in this year's draft. There are reasons to be cautious with all rookie QBs, but it’s hard not to get excited. New HC Kliff Kingsbury's offense was prolific and he was able to reload the roster with WRs he handpicked to fit the scheme. QBs that can rush like Murray rarely have the passing acumen that he possesses.
fields.key_to_championship: Literally everything has to fall into place. Murray has to be the best rookie quarterback of all time. Hakeem Butler must catch every pass Murray throws to him. Kerryon Johnson must have the much desired 1000/1000 season. So, not a lot of hope.
fields.scouting_report: "The Bruisers have been bruised since the beginning. I don't see many wins in 2019, but I wouldn't be surprised if one year from now we will be looking at a much better team. The squad is young and very promising."

fields.name: Garðabær Gorillas
fields.description: Garðabær Gorillas are one of two new teams this season. General Manager, Haffi, has a lot of work to do as he inherited arguably the worst roster in the league. The GM has shown that he is not afraid of making changes and is already one of the most active traders in the league. He seeks to find value in the middle rounds of rookie drafts as he had 5 picks in rounds 2 and 3 this year and has already been prepping the 2020 draft as he has no less than 4 picks just in the 2nd round. The Gorillas used their first 3 picks on two wide receivers and a tight end and made a few dart throws in the later rounds on running backs. They will need to address their running back need soon, but they do have a solid foundation of receivers to build on.
fields.quarterbacks: If there is one position you get away with having older players, it's the quarterback position. Philip Rivers should be starting most games for the Gorillas this year and is capable enough to lead a fantasy team. Case Keenum will back him up on the bye week and bad matchups. The General Manager did see a need for a 3rd quarterback and used their 4th round pick on rookie Daniel Jones, who might even replace Eli Manning this season.
fields.running_backs: This is by far the worst position on the Gorillas roster. Their best player, Kareem Hunt, is suspended for the  first 8 weeks and joined a new team after some questionable decisions in his personal life. Latavius Murray is no. 2 on the depth chart, both for the Gorillas and the Saints. The good news is though that the Saints 2nd running back usually scores more points than many teams' 1st back. After that there isn't much to work with and the GM will have a hard time filling the position on bye weeks or even until Hunt returns. The rest consists of 73 year old Frank Gore and his 4 grandchildren rookies.
fields.receivers: The receiver position is going through a change for the Gorillas, former elite receivers are in their last years or have even retired and young blood is rising up. Kenny Golladay is a foundational player to build the team around. 2nd year D.J. Moore has already shown flashes of greatness and might become Cam's favourite weapon for the coming years. Even though rookie wide receivers tend to have a slow start, Parris Campbell might make an impact in year one with Andrew Luck. Larry Fitzgerald might be playing his last season but should be good enough for the flex spot most week. Rookie Marquise Brown and Quincy Enunwa will be fighting for a starting spot as well. GM Haffi spent their 2nd round pick on a position the desperately needs help. Given the lack of talent at the tight end position, Noah Fant might slide straight into the starting line-up. 2nd year player Mike Gesicki might get a few games though.
fields.all_eyes_on: It's clear that the Lions view Golladay as their long-term WR1, though you do have to wonder just how high his ceiling will be. Despite Golden Tate leaving and Marvin Jones missing time at the end of the season, Golladay finished as the No. 21 receiver in fantasy.  major problems are a run-heavy offensive and the return of Marvin Jones, who missed the final seven games in 2018.
fields.x_factor: Late in the 2nd Round of the NFL Draft, the Colts picked Parris Campbell. He ran a 4.31 40-yard dash at the NFL Combine, tied for fastest among wideouts. Like many rookie receivers, Campbell may not contribute much for fantasy in his rookie season, but the landing spot with Andrew Luck and the Colts is terrific.
fields.key_to_championship: I can't imagine any scenario where the Gorillas win the Championship this year, unless something catastrophic happens, but then we probably won't be thinking about fantasy football.
fields.scouting_report: "Division 3 should count themselves lucky to play 2 matches against the Gorillas this year. I don't see them winning more than 1-2 games this season. The good news is though that they have a young and promising receiving core to build on and could be a force in just a few years."
